InVivoStat (beta version) Paired t-test Analysis and Within-Subject Analysis

Warning

This output has been generated using the beta test version of InVivoStat. Care should be taken when making decisions based on the output.

Response, covariates and covariance structure

The Resp 1 response is currently being analysed by the Paired t-test Analysis and Within-Subject Analysis module, with Cov1, Cov7 and Cov8 fitted as covariates.

The response has been Log10 transformed prior to analysis.

The repeated measures mixed model analysis is using the unstructured covariance structure to model the within-subject correlations. When using this structure you are estimating many parameters. If the numbers of subjects used is small then these estimates may be unreliable, see Pinherio and Bates (2002).

Case profiles plot of the observed data (on the Log10 scale)

Plot of the response vs. the covariates (on the transformed scale), categorised by the primary factor

Tip: In order to decide whether it is helpful to fit the covariate, the following should be considered:

a) Is there a relationship between the response and the covariate? (N.B., It is only worth fitting the covariate if there is a strong positive (or negative) relationship between them: i.e., the lines on the plot should not be horizontal).

b) Is the relationship similar for all treatments? (The lines on the plot should be approximately parallel).

c) Is the covariate influenced by the treatment? (We assume the covariate is not influenced by the treatment and so there should be no separation of the treatment groups along the x-axis on the plot).

These issues are discussed in more detail in Morris (1999).

Diagnostic plots

Residuals vs. predicted plot

Tip: On this plot look to see if the spread of the points increases as the predicted values increase. If so the response may need transforming.

Tip: Any observation with a standardised residual less than -3 or greater than 3 (SD) should be investigated as a possible outlier.

Comment: The standardised residuals at level i are obtained by subtracting the fitted levels at that level from the response vector and dividing by the estimated within-group standard error.

Analysis description

The data were analysed using a repeated measures mixed model approach, with treatment factor Day1, Block1 as the blocking factor and Cov1, Cov7 and Cov8 as covariates.This was followed by planned comparisons on the predicted means to compare the levels of the Day1. The response was Log10 transformed prior to analysis to stabilise the variance.

The unstructured covariance structure allowed the variability of the responses to be different, depending on the level of Day1. This structure also allowed the correlation between responses from any pair of levels of Day1 to be different. While this approach is the most general it should be used with care when there are few subjects, as many parameters need to be estimated. These estimates may not be very reliable.

A full description of mixed model theory, including information on the R nlme package used by InVivoStat (beta version), can be found in Venables and Ripley (2003) and Pinherio and Bates (2002).

For more information on the theoretical approaches that are implemented within this module, see Bate and Clark (2014).
